nce of mass internment on the West Coast—largely because of the language barrier immigrant writers faced. This translation, therefore, presents us with a rare Issei voice on internment, and Soga’s opinions challenge many commonly held assumptions about Japanese Americans during the war regarding race relations, patriotism, and loyalty.Although centered on one man’s experience, Life behind Barbed Wire benefits greatly from Soga’s trained eye and instincts as a professional journalist, which allowed him to paint a larger picture of those extraordinary times and his place in them. The Introduction by Tetsuden Kashima of the University of Washington and Foreword by Dennis Ogawa of the University of Hawai‘i provide context for Soga’s recollections based on the most current scholarship on the Japanese American internment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aJapanese AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aJapanese AmericansxEvacuation and relocation, 1942-1945. 0aJapanese AmericansxForced removal and internment, 1942-1945. 0aJapanese AmericanszHawaiivBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, American. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJapanese Americans. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh1 aHirai, Kihei.1 aKashima, Tetsuden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKashima, Tetsuden.1 aOgawa, Dennis M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486335740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97808248633